[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    50[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Architecture diagram shows the inbound path [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mI1/I2/I3 (HIE / FHIR $match / PIX/PDQ) -> AG1 (API Gateway) -> Q1 (SQS realtime) -> L1 (normalize-query) -> L2 (evaluate-match) -> L3 (apply-consent-and-sensitivity) -> L4 (release-and-audit)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m; the outbound path [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mL4 -> L5 (outbound-query-submitter) -> NAT1 -> EXT1 (Partner Org / HIE Intermediary) -> L6 (aggregate-partner-responses) -> L4[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m; the invalidation path [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mEB1 -> L7 (invalidate-on-event)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m. Step 1 pseudocode [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mingest_query(inbound)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m calls [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mverify_requester_identity(inbound)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mis_purpose_of_use_permitted(principal, query.purpose_of_use)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m but the architecture text does not specify what those functions enforce. Step 5 pseudocode [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrelease_and_audit(query)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m writes the audit log and the EventBridge event without a specified caller-context check. The recipe's own TODO at the General Architecture Pattern (referenced as "Expert review S1 (HIGH)") names the gap and prescribes the chapter-pattern fix but the architecture text does not actually specify the boundary.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    51[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe specifies the cross-facility pipeline at flow-and-service granularity but is silent on the identity-boundary policy that controls who can invoke each path and what proves the caller is authorized to act on a particular patient record. The chapter-wide pattern from 4.4 through 5.4 has converged on a structured identity-boundary specification; Recipe 5.5 inherits the concern with five concrete attack surfaces:[K
