[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    466[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m1[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe invalidation timing on consent revocation is not specified.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m A consent-revocation event from the registry must propagate to the cache deletion before any subsequent query can read the cached state. Without explicit specification, the implementation may treat the invalidation as eventually-consistent (with seconds-to-minutes lag), during which time queries may release data the patient has just revoked consent for.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    467[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    468[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m2[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe in-flight-query handling on revocation is not specified.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m A query that has read the consent cache (the cached state shows consent permitted) and is in the middle of constructing the response may still release data after the registry's consent-revocation event has been emitted but before the in-flight query completes. The mitigation is to either (a) re-check consent at the release-and-audit step (synchronous read from the registry, not the cache), or (b) make the cache-read-and-release path atomic with respect to consent invalidation. The architecture does not specify either.[K
